<b>Floyd</b> | Baseball is a pretty complicated game with many arcane rules -- I doubt
<b>Floyd</b> | very many fans can explain the myriad ways in which a pitcher can
<b>Floyd</b> | commit a balk (I can't) -- but for purposes of Bonehead, you only need
<b>Floyd</b> | to know a very few things.  These can be learned by careful reading or
<b>Floyd</b> | trial and error during play, but the information below may be helpful
<b>Floyd</b> | for those unfamiliar with the game.
<b>Floyd</b> |
<b>Floyd</b> | You are a batter, a runner, and a fielder in this game.  As a batter,
<b>Floyd</b> | you stand at home plate, attempting to hit balls thrown by the pitcher
<b>Floyd</b> | by swinging a bat.  (The mechanics of swinging will be explained to you
<b>Floyd</b> | in-game; please make sure to talk to your teammates about the art of
<b>Floyd</b> | hitting).  During batting practice, the pitcher throws balls for you to
<b>Floyd</b> | hit easily.  In the "real" game, however, the pitcher is your opponent;
<b>Floyd</b> | he attempts to keep you from hitting the ball, or hitting it well.  If
<b>Floyd</b> | you swing and miss at a pitch, it is recorded as a strike against you.
<b>Floyd</b> | If you decline to swing at a pitch, but the umpire deems it to be
<b>Floyd</b> | within the strike zone (roughly, from your chest to your knees
<b>Floyd</b> | vertically, and the width of the plate horizontally), it is also
<b>Floyd</b> | recorded as a strike.  Three strikes, and you are out.  If the pitch is
<b>Floyd</b> | outside the strike zone, it is recorded as a ball.  Four balls, and you
<b>Floyd</b> | are granted first base automatically (a base on balls, or a walk).
<b>Floyd</b> |
<b>Floyd</b> | If you hit the ball in fair territory during the game, you must run to
<b>Floyd</b> | first base; and from there, possibly to second base, third base, and
<b>Floyd</b> | back to home plate, which scores a run for your team.  The team with
<b>Floyd</b> | the most runs at the end of the game is the winner.  Note that the
<b>Floyd</b> | batter is required to try to advance to first base if he hits the ball
<b>Floyd</b> | and it is not caught in the air by a fielder.  If there is already a
<b>Floyd</b> | runner at first base, that runner must try to advance to second base.
<b>Floyd</b> | If the ball arrives at second base before that runner does, the runner
<b>Floyd</b> | is forced out.
<b>Floyd</b> |
<b>Floyd</b> | As a fielder, you are on defense: your goal is to put out the opposing
<b>Floyd</b> | players.  One of the primary means of accomplishing this is to touch
<b>Floyd</b> | first base while in possession of the baseball, before the batter can
